course_name: Automata Theory
description: Explore finite automata, context-free grammars, Turing machines, and intractable problems in this comprehensive study of theoretical computer science foundations.

course_name: System Validation: Automata and behavioural equivalences
description: Explore automata and behavioral equivalences for system validation. Learn to model and analyze system behavior, understand equivalences, and design structurally sound embedded systems.

course_name: Formal Languages and Automata Theory
description: Introduction to Automata Theory, Languages and Computation

course_name: Theory of Automata and Computation
description: Theory of Automata/Computation, Formal Languages, DFA, NFA, CFG, CFL, Pushdown Automata, Turing Machine, Undecidability

course_name: Theory of Automata, Formal Languages and Computation
description: Explore automata theory, formal languages, and computation through grammars, finite state automata, pushdown automata, Turing machines, and advanced topics in theoretical computer science.

course_name: Greibach Normal Form and Conversion of Context Free Grammar to GNF in Automata Theory
description: Explore Greibach Normal Form and learn how to convert context-free grammars to GNF. Gain insights into this important concept in automata theory and formal language processing.

course_name: Learning Automata with Hankel Matrices - Borja Balle, Amazon Research Cambridge
description: Explore a unified framework for learning automata using Hankel matrices, covering query learning, spectral learning, and matrix completion algorithms with practical applications.

course_name: Deterministic Finite Automata
description: Explore deterministic finite automata, their structure, and applications in computer science. Learn to construct DFAs, understand regular languages, and solve computational problems.

course_name: Great Ideas in Theoretical Computer Science: Finite Automata
description: Explore finite automata and regular languages in theoretical computer science, covering DFAs, computation concepts, and language analysis techniques.

course_name: Formal Languages and Automata for Reward Function Specification and Efficient Reinforcement Learning
description: Explore formal languages and automata for specifying reward functions in reinforcement learning, focusing on Linear Temporal Logic and Reward Machines to address real-world RL challenges.

course_name: Fractal Dimensions and Büchi Automata
description: Explore fractal dimensions and Büchi automata, delving into formal definitions, regular languages, and ω-languages. Discover applications in model theory and intriguing examples where dimensions diverge.

course_name: Conversion of Regular Expression to Finite Automata Using Subset Method in Automata Theory
description: Learn to convert regular expressions to finite automata using the subset method, covering NFA construction, epsilon transition removal, and DFA conversion in automata theory.

course_name: Conversion of Finite Automata to Regular Expression Using State Eliminating Method in Automata Theory
description: Learn to convert finite automata to regular expressions using the state elimination method, a crucial technique in automata theory for simplifying complex systems.

course_name: Conversion of Finite Automata to Regular Expression Using Arden's Method in Automata Theory
description: Learn to convert finite automata to regular expressions using Arden's method in automata theory. Explore step-by-step process with examples to master this important concept in theoretical computer science.

course_name: PLSE Seminar Series - The Power of Symbolic Automata
description: Explores symbolic automata, their applications in program verification, and novel decision procedures for equivalence checking and minimization of these powerful automata operating over infinite alphabets.

course_name: An Introduction to Walnut - Lecture 1
description: Explore Walnut, a tool for automata-based decision procedures in number theory and combinatorics on words. Learn its applications and fundamental concepts.

course_name: An Introduction to Walnut - Lecture 2
description: Explore Walnut, a tool for automata-based proofs in number theory and combinatorics. Delve into advanced techniques and applications in this comprehensive mathematical lecture.

course_name: On Partial-Order and Automata Techniques for Analyzing Communication
description: Explores verification and synthesis techniques for peer-to-peer and mailbox communication in concurrent programming, focusing on message-passing models and their applications in distributed systems.

course_name: Challenges in Formalising Recent Results in Formal Language Theory
description: Explore challenges in formalizing recent results linking formal language theory and computational group theory, with insights on making proofs more amenable to formalization.

course_name: Weighted Finite State Automata and Linear Algebra - JSALT 2023 Team Presentation
instructor_name: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
course_institution: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
description: Explore weighted finite state automata and linear algebra in speech and language processing through a comprehensive JSALT 2023 team presentation by Lucas Ondel Yang.

course_name: Complete Multiparty Session Type Projection with Automata - ST30
description: Explore efficient multiparty session type projection using automata. Learn sound, complete, and efficient techniques for verifying asynchronous communication protocols.

course_name: Visualizing Why Nondeterministic Finite-State Automata Reject
description: Explore visual techniques for understanding rejection in nondeterministic finite-state automata, enhancing comprehension of complex computational concepts.

course_name: On Learning Polynomial Recursive Programs
description: Explore P-finite automata, a generalization of weighted automata with polynomial transition weights. Learn about their polynomial-time learnability in Angluin's MAT exact learning model.

course_name: Parikh's Theorem Made Symbolic - POPL'24
description: Explore Parikh's Theorem for symbolic automata, learning efficient algorithms for handling large or infinite alphabets in language processing and constraint solving.

course_name: What is “the mind” and what is artificial intelligence?
description: In this course, we will explore the history of cognitive science and the way these ideas shape how we think of artificial cognition.

course_name: System Validation (3): Requirements by modal formulas
description: Aprenda a especificar requisitos formais para sistemas usando lógica modal e fórmulas fixas, permitindo análise automatizada e garantia de comportamento correto em sistemas embarcados.

course_name: Theory of Computation
description: Explore finite automata, regular languages, context-free grammars, and Turing machines. Learn about computational models, their properties, and fundamental concepts in theoretical computer science.

course_name: Introduction to Automata, Languages and Computation
description: Automata, Languages and Computation have been an important part of the curriculum in computer science department for several decades.The automata theory is the study of abstract machines and theirapplication in solving computational problems

course_name: Continuity and Rational Functions - Michaël Cadilhac, University of Oxford
description: Explore continuity in word-to-word functions and its connection to language classes. Delve into transducers and their role in computing continuous functions, with applications in automata theory.

course_name: Automata-Theoretic Approach to Modelling Consciousness Within Mental Monism
description: Automata-theoretic approach to modeling consciousness in mental monism, exploring constraints and implications for substrate-free models of the mind's structure and dynamics.

course_name: Course Review Lecture Part 3 - Aug 10, 2012
description: Comprehensive review of digital logic concepts including flip-flops, registers, counters, and finite state machines. Covers design processes and practical applications in digital systems.

course_name: Digital Circuits Lecture - Summary - Finite State Machines
description: Comprehensive overview of Finite State Machines, covering problem understanding, diagram creation, state assignment, flip-flop selection, and implementation specifics for both Mealy and Moore machines.

course_name: Why It's All Snake Oil - And That May Be Ok
description: Explore cybersecurity challenges, computational limitations, and the implications of "snake oil" solutions in modern technology and threat detection.

course_name: Real Time Communication to Simplify Your Life
description: Explore real-time communication in IoT projects, focusing on connectivity, scalability, and global distribution. Learn about SIM card management, security, and PHP-based use cases in various industries.

course_name: Growing Neural Cellular Automata
description: Explore neural cellular automata that learn to grow complex patterns through local interactions, mimicking biological morphogenesis and self-organization in a fascinating, interactive model.

course_name: A Relational Exploration of the Chomsky Hierarchy
description: Explore encoding automata and Turing Machines in miniKanren for relational programming. Learn to generate strings and associated data structures, gaining insights into the Chomsky Hierarchy and automata workings.

course_name: SetState Machine
description: Explore deterministic state management in React components using State Machines. Learn Automata theory basics and discover how to generate automated tests for more predictable applications.

course_name: Games: From Logic and Automata to Algorithms
description: Explore the intersection of logic, automata, and algorithms through game theory, focusing on theoretical foundations and computational applications.

course_name: Reversible D-Dimensional CA Over the Ring ZM and Some Applications in Ergodic Theory
description: Explore cellular automata on $\mathbf{Z}_p$ and $\mathbf{Z}_m$, covering invertibility, ergodic properties, and entropy concepts. Delve into measure-theoretic and topological entropy for 1D linear CA and $\mathbb{Z}^2$-actions.

course_name: Why It’s All Snake Oil – And That May Be OK
description: Explore the limitations of security products, understand computer science theorems, and learn to evaluate vendor claims for your organization's needs.

course_name: Text Search Protocols with Simulation Based Security
description: Explore text search protocols with simulation-based security, covering applications, automata encryption, and evaluation techniques for secure and efficient data retrieval.

course_name: Cellular Automata: Algorithmic Information Dynamics in Living Systems
description: Explore cellular automata, a computational model for complex systems, and their applications in studying causality and living systems from networks to cells.

course_name: SLR Parser with Example in Compiler Design - Parse Table & Parse Tree
description: Learn to construct SLR parsers, including LR(0) canonical items, parse tables, and parse trees. Gain practical skills in compiler design through detailed examples and step-by-step explanations.

course_name: Chomsky Normal Form and Conversion of CFG to CNF in Automata Theory
description: Learn to convert Context-Free Grammars to Chomsky Normal Form, a standardized format for simplifying and analyzing grammars in automata theory. Understand the steps and rules for this important transformation.

course_name: Conversion of NFA with Epsilon to NFA Without Epsilon in Automata Theory
description: Learn to convert NFA with epsilon transitions to NFA without epsilon, a crucial skill in automata theory. Understand the step-by-step process and its importance in simplifying finite automata representations.

course_name: Tutorial on Cellular Automata - Lecture 2
description: Explore advanced concepts in cellular automata, including complex patterns and computational models, in this in-depth mathematical lecture.

course_name: Around Cobham's Theorem
description: Explore Cobham's theorem and its implications in combinatorics on words through an in-depth mathematical analysis.

course_name: Stabilizing Shifts of Finite Type with Cellular Automata
description: Explore stabilization of finite type shifts using cellular automata in this mathematical conference talk on dynamic system complexity.

course_name: Significance of Regular Languages and Regular Operations - Lecture 5
description: Explore regular languages, non-regular examples, and key operations like union, concatenation, and Kleene star to deepen understanding of formal language theory.

course_name: Reactive Synthesis - Open Questions and Challenges
description: Experts discuss open questions and challenges in reactive synthesis, exploring cutting-edge research and future directions in system modeling and automation.

course_name: Synthesis and Verification of Finite Horizon Tasks
description: Explore finite horizon task synthesis and verification techniques, focusing on model and system creation for time-bounded objectives in computational systems.

course_name: Specification-guided Reinforcement Learning
description: Explore specification-guided reinforcement learning techniques for synthesizing models and systems, presented by Rajeev Alur from the University of Pennsylvania.

course_name: Distributed Controller Synthesis for Deadlock Avoidance
description: Explore advanced techniques for synthesizing distributed controllers to prevent deadlocks in complex systems, enhancing system reliability and performance.

course_name: Synthesizing Distributed Protocols from Global Session Types
description: Automata-theoretic approach to synthesizing distributed protocols from global session types, introducing a sound and complete projection operator for multiparty session types.

course_name: Attractor Decompositions in Games and Automata
description: Explore attractor decompositions in graphs, their role in parity games, and applications to automata theory. Learn about structural complexity measures and strategy analysis.

course_name: Deciding Regular Games - A Playground for Exponential Time Algorithms
description: Explore exponential time algorithms for deciding regular games, examining their applications and implications in system design and analysis.

course_name: Automata-Based Approach for Quantum Circuit and Program Verification
description: Innovative automata-based technique for verifying quantum circuits, offering scalable analysis and bug detection through compact state representation and algebraic computations.

course_name: New Models of Games with Imperfect Information
description: Explores innovative approaches to modeling imperfect information in infinite games using finite-state automata, comparing observation-based and indistinguishability-relation models for enhanced expressiveness and strategy synthesis.

course_name: Synthesis of Privacy-Preserving Systems
description: Explore privacy-preserving system synthesis, addressing hidden signals, budget constraints, and incomplete information while satisfying specifications and protecting secrets.

course_name: Coxeter Groups are Biautomatic - Lecture 3
description: Explore Coxeter groups and their biautomatic properties in this advanced mathematics lecture, part of a comprehensive workshop on geometric group theory.

course_name: Coxeter Groups are Biautomatic - Lecture 2
description: Explore Coxeter groups' biautomatic properties in this advanced geometric group theory lecture, part of a workshop fostering research collaboration and exposure to active areas in the field.

course_name: Coxeter Groups are Biautomatic - Lecture 1
description: Explore Coxeter groups and their biautomatic properties in this advanced mathematics lecture, part of a comprehensive workshop on geometric group theory.

course_name: CLR(1) Parser in Compiler Design - Bottom-up Parsing and Types of LR Parsers
description: Explore CLR(1) parsing in compiler design, including bottom-up parsing techniques and various LR parser types. Gain insights into efficient syntax analysis for programming languages.

course_name: LR(0) Parser in Compiler Design - Bottom-up Parsing and Types of LR Parsers
description: Explore LR(0) parsing, bottom-up techniques, and LR parser types in compiler design. Learn key concepts for efficient syntax analysis and code generation.

course_name: Parse Tree and Derivation Trees in Compiler Design
description: Explore parse trees, left-most and right-most derivations, and derivation trees in compiler design. Learn key concepts for understanding language parsing and syntax analysis.

course_name: Specification of Tokens in Compiler Design - Regular Expressions, Languages, and Alphabets
description: Explore token specification in compiler design, covering regular expressions, languages, strings, and alphabets. Learn key concepts for effective lexical analysis and token recognition.

course_name: Elimination of Left Recursion in Compiler Design - Examples and Explanation
description: Explore left recursion in compiler design, its impact on parsing, and techniques for elimination. Learn to identify and resolve left-recursive grammars for efficient parsing.

course_name: LEX: Language Specifying Lexical Analyzer - Compiler Design
description: Explore LEX, a powerful tool for creating lexical analyzers in compiler design. Learn its functionality, usage, and implementation in language processing.

course_name: Recognition of Tokens in Compiler Design - Transition Tables and Diagrams
description: Explore token recognition in compiler design, including transition tables and diagrams. Learn key concepts for understanding lexical analysis and automata theory in compilation processes.

course_name: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love Evaluations (and Keep Worrying)
instructor_name: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
course_institution: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
description: Explore the benefits and challenges of coordinated evaluations in NLP research, focusing on recent work in low-resource languages and semantic parsing.

course_name: Machine Translation: Automata Theory, Probability, and Linguistics - 2007
instructor_name: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
course_institution: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
description: Explore machine translation's evolution through automata theory, probability, and linguistics. Delve into tree-based models and their impact on natural language processing.

course_name: Finite State Methods with Modern Neural Architectures for Speech Applications and Beyond
instructor_name: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
course_institution: Center for Language & Speech Processing(CLSP), JHU
description: Explore finite state methods integrated with neural architectures for advanced speech applications and beyond in this comprehensive JSALT 2023 workshop.

course_name: Classical and Quantum Conway Game of Life - Methodologies and Applications
description: Explore classical and quantum Conway Game of Life methodologies, including stochastic models, dissipative Schrödinger equations, and thermodynamic aspects. Gain insights into complex systems and quantum mechanics applications.

course_name: Pattern Explorer Tool for Testing CEP Patterns
description: Explore a tool for testing Complex Event Processing patterns through automata compilation and symbolic event sequence generation. Enhance pattern understanding and error detection in event streams.

course_name: Regular Expression Matching using Bit Vector Automata
description: Explore a new algorithm for efficient regex matching with bounded repetition using nondeterministic bit vector automata, offering improved performance for challenging patterns in practice.

course_name: A Direct ASP Encoding for Declare
description: Explore a novel ASP encoding for Declare constraints in Process Mining, comparing its effectiveness to alternative approaches for improved business process modeling.

course_name: Efficient Matching of Regular Expressions with Lookaround Assertions
description: Explore efficient matching of regular expressions with lookaround assertions, including formal semantics, simplification properties, and a new O(m·n) algorithm using oracle-NFAs for improved performance.

course_name: Additive Cellular Automata Graded-Monadically
description: Explore cellular automata through graded comonadic and monadic perspectives, focusing on additive variants and their computational implications.

course_name: Visualizing a Nondeterministic to Deterministic Finite-State Machine Transformation
description: Explore the visualization of transforming nondeterministic finite-state machines to deterministic ones in this insightful presentation.

course_name: States, Transitions and a Bit of Code
description: Explore state management, transitions, and coding techniques in UI development for creating dynamic and responsive user interfaces.

course_name: Derivative Based Nonbacktracking Real-World Regex Matching with Backtracking Semantics
description: Explore a new derivative-based theory and algorithm for nonbacktracking regex matching, supporting anchors and counting while preserving backtracking semantics. Implemented in .NET7 with formal proof of correctness.

course_name: Deciding Asynchronous Hyperproperties for Recursive Programs
description: Explore a novel logic for asynchronous hyperproperties, enhancing model checking for recursive programs. Gain insights into temporal logic, automata theory, and pushdown systems.

course_name: An Automata-Based Framework for Verification and Bug Hunting in Quantum Circuits
description: Explore a novel automata-based approach for analyzing quantum circuits, enabling efficient verification and bug detection in large-scale quantum systems using tree automata and algebraic representations.

course_name: 理论计算机科学基础 | Introduction to Theoretical Computer Science
description:
本课程内容涵盖了形式语言与自动机理论、可计算性理论、计算复杂性理论等最基本的那部分内容。
This course covers the most basic parts of formal language and automata theory, computability theory and computational complexity theory.

course_name: 离散数学概论 Discrete Mathematics Generality
description:
离散数学是计算机科学的基础理论，离散结构的基础知识和逻辑思维的形式化是信息技术类学生的基本功，离散数学的基本概念是理科专业学生进行信息类课程学习的重要基础。

本课程介绍计算机科学和信息技术理论基础的概念和思想方法，介绍数理逻辑、集合论、图论、抽象代数和形式语言与自动机等各部分的基本概念，介绍离散数学基本概念和空间信息技术之间的联系与结合，培养学生理解和掌握离散数学基本概念，采用形式化方法分析问题，并能自觉运用逻辑分析、结构层次分析和同构类比等思想方法解决问题的能力。

course_name: Theory of Computation
